06772nam a22006735i 9780773588769DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20132013xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735887697 a10.1515/97807735887692doi  a(DE-B1597)657835  a(OCoLC)857960080  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHB121.I56 ǂb H37 2013eb 7aHIS0060002bisacsh04a338.97191 aBuxton, William J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHarold Innis and the North :bAppraisals and Contestations /cWilliam J. Buxton. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (368 p.) :b9 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: North by Northwest: Harold Innis and “the Advancement of Knowledge of the Canadian North” -- tInnis and Northern Canada: Fur Trade and Nation -- tHarold Innis, Peter Pond, and the Fur Trade -- tThe Northern Vision of Harold Innis -- tHarold Innis’s Overlooked 1924 Memo on Wildlife Conservation in Northern Canada: The State, Staples, and the Economics of Conservation -- tA Confidential Memorandum on the Conservation of Wild Life in the Mackenzie District, prepared at the request of Mr. Hoyes Lloyd, and submitted to him by Mr. Harold A. Innis of the Department of Political Economy, University of Toronto -- tInnis, Biss, and Industrial Circuitry in the Canadian North, 1921–1965 -- tHarold Adams Innis and Northern Manitoba -- tThe Newfoundland and Labrador Fieldwork of Harold Adams Innis -- tBringing Nordicity to the South City: Harold Innis as Reviewer of Books on the North, 1928–1944 -- tNorth-South Networks of Knowledge: Harold Innis, the Rockefeller Foundation, and the Canadian Social Science Research Council’s Arctic Survey -- tArctic Surveillance: Innis, the Arctic Survey, and Canadian State Agencies -- tNorthern Enlightenment: Innis’s 1945 Trip to Russia and Its Aftermath -- tTowards the “Second Renaissance”: A Russian Perspective on Innis’s Russian Diary -- tInnis and Environmental Politics: Practical Insights from the Yukon -- tInnis and I on the Highway of the Atom -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHarold Innis is widely understood as the proponent of the "Laurentian school" of historiography, which mapped Canadian development along an East-West axis. Harold Innis and the North turns the axis North-South by examining Innis's intense and abiding interest in the North, and providing new perspectives on this seminal figure in Canadian political economy and communication studies. This collection reveals that Innis's advocacy of the North was closely bound up with his vision of northern Canada as the site of a second industrial revolution based on mining, hydro-electric power, pulp and paper, and enabled by new forms of transportation. Long preoccupied with Canada's coming of age as a balanced and integrated industrial nation-state, Innis grappled with the same issues about the North in the Canadian nation that we are dealing with today. Chapters explore the breadth of Innis's northern activities, including his early studies of the fur trade, his biography of eighteenth-century explorer and cartographer Peter Pond, his review essays on the North for the Canadian Historical Review, his leadership of the Rockefeller-sponsored Arctic Survey, and his trip to the Soviet Union. Harold Innis and the North crafts a new narrative about the nature and scope of Innis's intellectual project and provides a unique appreciation of his multi-faceted professional identity. Contributors include Sergei Arkhipov (North-Ossetian State University and NGO Vladikavkaz Institute of Economics) Jeffrey Brison (Queens), George Colpitts (Calgary), Matthew Evenden (UBC), Barry Gough (Churchill College, Cambridge and Kings College, London), Paul Heyer (Wilfrid Laurier), Jim Mochoruk (North Dakota), Liza Piper (Alberta), Shirley Roburn (Concordia), Peter van Wyck (Concordia), Jeff Webb (Memorial).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCanada, NorthernxHistoriography. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh1 aArkhipov, Sergei, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrison, Jeffrey D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuxton, William J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColpitts, George, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvenden, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGough, Barry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeyer, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aInnis, Harold Adams, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMochoruk, Jim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPiper, Liza, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoburn, Shirley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVan Wyck, Peter C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWebb, Jeff A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013z978311127412608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013z978311127715840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358876940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773588769423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773588769/original  a978-3-11-127412-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package